ph/scheduler/jobs.py` lines 76-229\n- **Current state**: The `pipeline_job()` function is 154 lines and follows a repeating pattern for each pipeline phase (scrape, enrich, aggregate): open a Sentry span, log start, run orchestrator in try/except, capture exception on failure, set Sentry context, log finish. Each phase block is ~40 lines.\n- **Problem**: The three phase blocks follow the same structural pattern but the boilerplate (Sentry span, try/except/capture, set_context, logging) obscures the actual orchestration logic. The \"did phase succeed?\" check and \"skip if previous failed\" guard are repeated manually for each phase.\n- **Suggested simplification**: Extract a helper that encapsulates the run-a-phase pattern:\n\n```python\nasync def _run_phase(\n    phase_name: str,\n    span_op: str,\n    span_name: str,\n    run_fn: Callable,\n    context_fn: Callable,\n) -> bool:\n    with sentry_sdk.start_span(op=span_op, name=span_name):\n        logger.info(\"[%s] Starting %s phase\", phase_name.upper(), phase_name)\n        try:\n            result = await run_fn()\n            success = context_fn(result)\n        except Exception:\n            logger.exception(\"[%s] Phase failed\", phase_name.upper())\n            sentry_sdk.capture_exception()\n            success = False\n        logger.info(\"[%s] Phase finished: success=%s\", phase_name.upper(), success)\n        return success\n```\n\nHowever, each phase has enough unique context-setting and summary-building logic that the abstraction may trade boilerplate for a less-readable callback-based pattern. A more conservative approach: extract just the shared try/except/sentry pattern and keep phase-specific logic inline.\n\n- **Estimated line reduction**: ~30 lines\n- **Risk**: Medium -- the phases are similar but not identical (scrape stores run, enrichment has pass1/pass2 summaries, aggregation has different result shape). Over-abstracting could reduce readability. A conservative refactor (extracting just the try/except wrapper) is safer than a full phase-runner abstraction.\n\n---\n\n#### 7. `orchestrator.py` `_scrape_company_with_isolation` has a redundant stop-request check -- Priority: P2\n\n- **File(s)**: `/Users/vmud/Documents/dev/projects/compgraph/src/compgraph/scrapers/orchestrator.py` lines 333-393\n- **Current state**: The method checks `self._stop_requested` twice: once before acquiring the semaphore (lines 340-347) and once after acquiring it (lines 353-360). Both checks produce identical `ScrapeResult` objects with the same error message and set the same `CompanyState.SKIPPED` state.\n- **Problem**: The two checks produce identical 8-line blocks (16 lines total for what is logically one guard). The pre-semaphore check is an optimization to avoid queuing behind other tasks when a stop is already requested, so it is not purely redundant -- but the code blocks are identical.\n- **Suggested simplification**: Extract the stop-check into a private method `_make_skipped_result(company) -> ScrapeResult` and call it from both locations. This reduces the duplication to two 4-line blocks.\n\n```python\ndef _make_skipped_result(self, company: Company, run: PipelineRun) -> ScrapeResult:\n    run.company_states[company.slug] = CompanyState.SKIPPED\n    return ScrapeResult(\n        company_id=company.id,\n        company_slug=company.slug,\n        errors=[\"Skipped: pipeline stop requested\"],\n        finished_at=datetime.now(UTC),\n    )\n```\n\n- **Estimated line reduction**: ~10 lines\n- **Risk**: Low -- pure extraction of identical logic.\n\n---\n\n### Impact Summary\n\n| # | Finding | Priority | Est. Lines Saved | Risk |\n|---|---------|----------|-----------------|------|\n| 1 | Duplicate `persist_posting` across adapters | P0 | ~60 | Low |\n| 2 | Duplicate circuit breaker logic | P1 | ~25 (net 0, single source) | Low |\n| 3 | Verbose retry logic in orchestrator | P1 | ~25 | Low |\n| 4 | iCIMS does not use `RawPosting` dataclass | P1 | ~10 | Low |\n| 5 | Deepl